Introduction

In todayâ€™s fast-paced financial markets, understanding and forecasting stock behavior is essential for investors, traders, and analysts. This project explores the time series dynamics of NVIDIA (NVDA) by analyzing its adjusted stock prices, volatility, and trading volume. We leverage modern forecasting techniquesâ€”namely, Facebookâ€™s Prophet modelâ€”and classical statistical methods like linear regression and STL decomposition. By combining these approaches, we aim to forecast future trends and decompose the time series into its fundamental components: trend, seasonality, and residuals.

Data and Methodology

Data Acquisition

Historical data for NVIDIA was sourced from Yahoo Finance. The dataset spans from January 1, 2015, to the present, capturing daily adjusted closing prices and trading volume. Daily log returns are computed, and a 30-day rolling window is applied to estimate volatility. These measures form the basis for our analysis.

Forecasting with Prophet

Prophet is a robust forecasting tool that models time series data by capturing trends, seasonality, and holiday effects. In our analysis, we built separate Prophet models for both daily and monthly data:

  • Daily Forecasts:
    Prophet is applied to daily volatility and trading volume. The forecasts include a confidence interval, giving an idea of the uncertainty surrounding the predictions. Linear regression trends are overlaid on the historical data to serve as a baseline for comparison.

  • Monthly Forecasts:
    To better capture long-term trends and seasonal effects, daily data are aggregated to the monthly level. Both the average monthly volatility and the total monthly trading volume are modeled and forecasted with Prophet.

Classical Methods: Linear Regression and STL Decomposition

In addition to Prophet, linear regression is applied to each chart to highlight long-term trends. Furthermore, STL (Seasonal-Trend decomposition using Loess) is employed on the monthly aggregates. STL decomposition breaks the time series into: - Trend: The long-term movement. - Seasonal: The repeating periodic fluctuations. - Residual: The noise or irregular variation.

The amplitude of the seasonal component is calculated to quantify the size of seasonal variations in both volatility and trading volume.
